  {
    "slug": "on-the-reaction-to-the-death-of-pope-francis",
    "title": "On The Reaction To The Death Of Pope Francis: Press Check",
    "subtitle": "A Critique of Australia's Media and Political Response",
    "stream": [
      "presscheck",
      "atheism"
    ],
    "briefType": null,
    "date": "December 6, 2025",
    "substackUrl": "https://outpostmedia.substack.com/p/on-the-reaction-to-the-death-of-pope",
    "thumbnail": "https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7cb99867-bc5f-4adc-92c5-a251ba274d8c_1024x963.jpeg",
    "content": "\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7cb99867-bc5f-4adc-92c5-a251ba274d8c_1024x963.jpeg\" alt=\"On The Reaction To The Death Of Pope Francis\" class=\"article-hero-img\">\n\n      <p><em>I originally wrote this piece the morning following the death of Pope Francis. Initially I wasn't planning on putting it online. I wasn't confident to post something so close to someone's death with the tone that piece eventually took on. And to be honest, I wasn't sure if there was enough substance to justify posting. However, time has passed, and I do believe there is something to the point I was trying to make. So here we are.</em></p>\n\n      <p><em>I make the caveat below, but it's worth making again: this piece essentially has nothing to do with Pope Francis as an individual; it's about the reaction to his death and what that represents.</em></p>\n\n      <hr>\n\n      <p>Pope Francis died on the 21st of April this year at 88 years of age. It is not the life of Pope Francis, his legacy, nor his actions as Pope that I wish to discuss, but the reaction here in Australia to his death and the role of the Pope, Christianity and religion in Australian politics and media.</p>\n\n      <p>In short, I found that the magnitude of the reaction from Australian media and politicians surprising (albeit perhaps naively), but mainly I thought it was overblown. In fact, I believe the whole cultural moment is demonstrative of a problem in our media and politics.</p>\n\n      <p>Getting straight to the point, I didn't feel any <em>deep</em> sense of emotion when I learned of Pope Francis's death yesterday. I don't like to read of people's death – especially from what I understand was a good, moral person's death – that (almost) goes without saying. To those who feel grief at the news, I give my condolences.</p>\n\n      <p>However, I cannot pretend or assume that I was the only person who felt essentially zero emotion at reading this news here in Australia; perhaps even <em>most</em> of the population did.</p>\n\n      <p>I want to be clear that the following really has nothing to do with Pope Francis himself at all, and I would not want to disrespect someone who passed as recently as the previous day (at the time of writing). The comments below are centred <em>purely</em> on the reaction and its illuminating effect on Australian society.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Media's Reaction</h2>\n\n      <p>When I opened the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) news app this morning, the first <em>five</em> stories were all related to Pope Francis, and two more were found only a short scroll down.</p>\n\n      <p>I can understand having two to three stories covering the event. After all, despite my position on religions in modern society, the man had a role of great influence and power, and thus it is very much a newsworthy event. However, I'd be much more comfortable with one article describing the pure facts of the matter, another on how things unfold from here (such as the election of the new pope) and perhaps one on his legacy as an individual. However, seven stories in the first 10-15 articles are too much in my opinion.</p>\n\n      <p>The amount of information and articles put out on a news publications website are directly proportional to the significance of the story. Or at least that's the implied takeaway. It's not rocket science to say a story that stays on the cutting room floor is likely not very important and one that makes the front page is. Note the use of 'likely'; of course this doesn't always hold, but the point is that it should.</p>\n\n      <p>In this case, half of the first dozen or so stories implies that this is one of the most important stories of the year. Trump's tariffs wiping out <a href=\"https://www.afr.com/markets/equity-markets/90b-wipeout-in-superannuation-wealth-could-force-rba-to-cut-rates-20250404-p5lp4u\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">$90 billion</a> of Australians super funds, Putin's indication of an agreement to a <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-03-12/ukraine-ready-to-accept-ceasefire-as-us-lifts-weapons-block/105039970\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">ceasefire over Easter</a> with Ukraine, and Trump's flurry of executive orders are all news events that received fewer stories in their immediate aftermath than Pope Francis's death did.</p>\n\n      <p>While this may simply reflect that it was a slow news day, I think the implication of the significance of the event by the number of stories has a real and true impact on the Australian psyche and zeitgeist. The ABC, as the publicly funded broadcaster who claims to reach 80% of Australians monthly, has a responsibility to treat the magnitude of every news story with care.</p>\n\n      <p>If someone actually bothered to click through all seven links, they'd discover that there was a significant amount of information overlap across the stories. So perhaps from a purely unique informational perspective, it was on par with the significance of the event. But the number of articles matters; in fact, I'd argue it's even more important when discussing the imprint on society and the reflection it shows (no matter how distorted).</p>\n\n      <p>Many consumers of modern news via social media and mobile applications scroll through the options and merely skim the headlines, choosing to ignore most of the articles available. Nonetheless, consuming the headline information shapes the perception of events both domestically and abroad. What someone who scrolls past all these stories will interpret is that the Pope's death is a story of the utmost importance. The fact is (I believe) it isn't.</p>\n\n      <p>The Pope's death will not impact the vast, vast majority of Australians in a day-to-day sense at all. Some will grieve, likely not long, although some will, but the truth of the matter is that even hardcore Christians' lives are not really affected in any medium- to long-term sense by the death of Pope Francis. It is simply the truth to say it isn't that important of a story for the ABC to justify such an excess of articles.</p>\n\n      <p>Australians, the ABC and I personally, acknowledge and celebrate that we are a multicultural society. Yet you'd think we were the US or the Vatican itself based on the coverage. In reality only <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-04-23/the-changing-face-of-catholicism-in-australia/104967032\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">20% of Australians</a> identify as Catholic and <a href=\"https://www.abs.gov.au/articles/religious-affiliation-australia#key-findings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">44% as Christian</a> based on 2021 census data. Again, even many of this 44% will not be particularly affected emotionally, and even fewer in any material sense.</p>\n\n      <h2>Why Does This Matter?</h2>\n\n      <p>Because it is unrepresentative and misleading. The nature of the coverage implies we should care; the news is supposed to inform us on the events that matter to us.</p>\n\n      <p>On the multiculturalism point – on a macro scale our society is mostly secular. We have the separation of church and state, and we have a deep mix of cultures and religions in our society.</p>\n\n      <p>If we are to successfully navigate the challenges of multiculturalism, then we must be honest enough to say that Christianity isn't critical to our society anymore. We shouldn't pretend or imply that it is. It's disrespectful to followers of Islam, Judaism, Hinduism, etc., and particularly to atheists.</p>\n\n      <p>The Pope is dead; people should know, and people should have the option to learn what they wish about the man himself, what he is connected to and what he represents.</p>\n\n      <p>However, ultimately, for the vast majority of Australians it's no different from the death of a celebrity whose name they're vaguely aware of. It's simply not that big of a deal, and ABC has a responsibility to reflect that in their broadcasting.</p>\n\n      <p>The fact is Australian taxpayer dollars are being spent to pump out several articles for the death of an 88-year-old man who had pneumonia in both lungs, who wasn't an important figure in <em>at least</em> 55% of the public's lives. I just cannot help but feel as if this is poor allocation of resources and that it distorts the perception of those consuming the content with the true reality of the situation on the ground.</p>\n\n      <h2>Side Note</h2>\n\n      <p>I want to briefly address a potential counterpoint on this matter. I can see an argument that would state that perhaps it was only my personal and unique particular feed that contained so many stories in sequence and therefore my criticism is overblown.</p>\n\n      <p>To that I would say, if the algorithm has been giving me all these stories which I do not care for, then perhaps it isn't a very good algorithm. Given that the ABC's budget is over <a href=\"https://budget.gov.au/content/bp4/download/bp4_2025-26-consolidated.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">$1 billion</a> annually, you would hope that the algorithm does a better job of providing articles that are a better match.</p>\n\n      <p>Or if it acts like other social media apps, where it will provide content that is likely to generate strong emotions like outrage to generate engagement, then that's an issue as well. I'd think it fair to say that the publicly funded broadcaster shouldn't be prioritising content designed to outrage – instead of, say, inform – but maybe I'm asking for too much.</p>\n\n      <h2>The Political Reaction</h2>\n\n      <p>One such article discussed some actions our politicians – mainly Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton – took following the Pope's death. This includes the Prime Minister's (Albanese's) decision to fly the Australian flag at half-mast out of respect, as well as both major party leaders declaring there would be no election campaigning for the day to honour Pope Francis and his legacy. Peter Dutton was quoted saying it was not a day for \"<em>big politicking</em>\".</p>\n\n      <p>I have no problem with the half-mast flag decision; it's an appropriate symbolic gesture made out of respect. It's the statements by Anthony Albanese and Peter Dutton to stop campaigning for a day that irk me.</p>\n\n      <p>It has <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-04-20/nsw-easter-drowning-toll-rises-fisherman-swept-rocks-wattamolla/105195098\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">been reported</a> that six people drowned over the Easter weekend off the coast of NSW, including a nine-year-old boy. Surf Life Saving NSW said it was the \"<em>worst</em>\" Easter long weekend on record.</p>\n\n      <p>My question is, why does Pope Francis' death constitute a justification for a day off campaigning but not the tragic death of six Australian citizens?</p>\n\n      <p>On one hand you have Pope Francis's, who was an 88-year-old man, non-Australian citizen, who lived a long life full of fulfilment, wealth and admiration. On the other you have six Australians who died long before their time, under tragic circumstances, including a child.</p>\n\n      <p>Are either of these men aware of what kind of message this sends? Particularly to the victims' families but also secular and non-Christian Australians.</p>\n\n      <p>Peter Dutton says Pope Francis death means it isn't a day for \"<em>big politicking</em>\" but has nothing to say in a similar vein for the drowning victims. The implication here is that the death of the drowning victims is still very much a day for 'big politicking'.</p>\n\n      <p>Frankly, it's bordering on disgraceful. Less than two weeks out from a federal election, your position is to spend 9% (1 of 11 days left) of the remaining time 'on pause'?</p>\n\n      <p>Sure, both Albanese and Dutton are both Christians, and thus it is very understandable for them to be experiencing grief of some kind, but the key point is they are also Australians, and critically, they're Australians who are vying to be the leader of our country, who I would hope would also be grieving at the death of those who drowned over the weekend, dare I say more so.</p>\n\n      <p>What the bipartisan pause on campaigning also demonstrates is how church and state are often more interlinked than we might think. Here we have our two major party leaders, whose salary is paid by tax dollars, essentially taking a 'day off' due to their religion and not because it's a holy day of some kind.</p>\n\n      <p>To further the point, since World War 1, as far as I understand, only five prime ministers were non-religious (Gorton, Curtin, Whitlam, Hawke and Gillard). Many are essentially just nominally religious, but nonetheless I think that counts for a lot.</p>\n\n      <p>So much for separation of church and state.</p>\n\n      <p>Side note: This point on nominally religious people is also interesting when considering the 2021 census data quoted earlier. Of the 44% who claimed to be Christian, many are likely to be merely nominally Christian in most ways and likely agnostic/atheists on many religious aspects.</p>\n\n      <p>In the end <a href=\"https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-04-22/anthony-albanese-peter-dutton-pope-francis-orange-andrew-gee/105199184\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">both party leaders</a> essentially did keep campaigning. Albanese held a press conference where he made statements about the Pope's death despite already releasing a statement the night before but also answered unrelated political questions. Similarly, Peter Dutton went on the radio to discuss the Pope's death but also discussed other political matters.</p>\n\n      <p>Do both instances not seem like standard-issue campaign acts? Which doesn't even mention the fact that both continued ahead with the third federal election debate in Sydney <em>that very night</em>. Does it get more campaign-like than a debate?</p>\n\n      <p>Now this may slightly undermine the point I made above, but I think the critical part of that was the messaging, not the actual action (or intended inaction in this case), along with the clear continued connection of church and state.</p>\n\n      <p>What the 'pseudo-pause' shows us, which is far worse than either of the above problems, is that all Albanese and Dutton have really done is blatantly lie to the public they're trying to convince of their worthiness.</p>\n\n      <p>Ironically, a rather unchristian act from both men. Something tells me, however, we won't get any admission of sin, and there certainly won't be any forgiveness given.</p>\n\n      <img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Facca5f58-3cef-425f-82bd-ecef0357a2ad_1024x970.jpeg\" alt=\"On The Reaction To The Death Of Pope Francis closing image\" class=\"article-img\">\n    "
  }
